data.title: A day in the life of a Freelance Voice Actor

tags.name: adayinthelife
tags.description: Share a day in your life to earn the exclusive trophy! (8/28 - 8/30)

images.description:
Am I too late for one of these #adayinthelife posts?

In any case, I wanted to create this post because many of you continue to show great interest in what I do and it has been a few years since I last made an educational post about the subject.

I am a freelance voice actor.
My first gig was in September 2013 so I am nearing my 10 year anniversary.

I have told my story of how I got into the field alongside a guide on how to best get started in this post: 

"How to get started as a voice actor?" - https://imgur.com/gallery/QvvaK"

The advice in it should still hold up, altough I have to mention that the market has been saturated the last couple of years with lowball offers from people creating "Cash Cow" YouTube channels. My advice is to stay as far away from those offers as you can.

-----

In any case, my day as a freelance voice actor starts with me getting out of bed and going to work at my day job.

Yeah, surprise, even after 10 years, I still need to have a day job. I have gotten better and better gigs the longer that I have done this, but most of them are one off jobs, not recurring.
The hourly pay can vary greatly from well above to well below minimum wage.
And since I am from Denmark, you may ask if I mean the Danish minimum wage or the US minimum wage. Well, to qoute Futurama: First one, then the other.

If you don't love doing it, you wont last long. There are long stretches of time where I have no work and then suddenly I can have 4-7 clients in the same week. Excpect evening/night hours and expect impatient clients.

-----
When I get home from my day job and if I have any clients I first do one thing that is counterintuitive.

I relax.

I've learned that for the voice to work properly, the body needs to be relaxed. I don't know if this is for everyone, but when I get home from work, I am not relaxed, so I have found that I am simply unable to do any voice over work for at least an hour or two after coming home. I prefer to do the work on the weekends if possible or on Wednesdays where I don't work my day job.

-----
When first starting out, YOU NEED TO DO VOCAL EXERCISES!!!
I cannot stress this enough. Since I started, my natural speaking voice has lowered over an octave. That's a lot.
All because I didn't use my voice correctly before.

And even for experienced voice users it is just as necessary. The other day, I had a 2 hour vocal exercise session, where I did vocal warm ups, singing exercises, physical exercises to strengthen my core, and a lot more. As a voice actor, your voice is your sole provider... you need to take care of it.

-----
Be patient.
It will take time. When you start out, you might quickly realize that you didn't have that natural talent that you always thought you had. I certainly did.

And it can easily feel like no progress ever takes place.

But then you listen to a recording you did previously and realize how far you have come.

I have a bunch of old recordings that I have thought about trying to rerecord and make a post here with the before and after audio.
If that's something you would want to see, let me know. I'll probably do it anyway at some point or another, but it's been on my to do list for over a year at this point, so if a bunch of you would be interested in it, it might get me to get off my ass and actually do it.

This was some clips for my character show-reel that I made about a year ago. I'm still pretty proud of them, but even so, I can hear lots of things that I could improve upon with what I have learned since then.

-----
During the recording process.

I have streamlined my process a lot over the years. I edit the audio myself. I remove background noise, compress, normalize and all of that.
Don't be frightened by the technical terms if you don't know what they mean. The most important part is Noise Reduction.

Use Audacity and search for tutorials and then just focus on learning one new thing at a time. Over the span of a few months you will have learned all the necessary things.

-----
Can it ever pay the bills?

Absolutely... Maybe... A definite perhaps...!

If you keep at it, you will build up a repetorie and your skill level. That will land you better jobs and you will be able to charge more.

At some point, there will be the possibility to get recurring work.

I just signed the contract for a recurring (well-paid) gig as a YouTube host for a group that has lots of channels in different genres. (Hence the green screen and studio lights in the picture)
That has the potential to become quite lucrative.

I've also closed a deal with someone who makes fanmade marvel audiodramas with lots of recurring work, when they begin production on their new pieces in december.

I auditioned to voice 4 villians from spiderman:
- Green Goblin
- Venom
- Kingpin
- The Vulture

I ended up gettin all 4 roles plus the voice for Norman Osborne, and eventually Harry Osborne and his Goblin character. Also the voice for Eddie Brock, who is venom without the symbiote.
https://imgur.com/gallery/akTsPgO

images.description:
TL;DR - I want to work, but it doesn't seem in the cards. 

In 2022, I graduated with my master's as a mid-life career change (I'm 40). I have 20 years prior experience in administrative assistant work/office management/accounting. In 2019, I went back to school and finished my bachelor's degree, and since the pandemic was still raging, I continued and finished my master's in a year so I could get to work faster. 

I had one interview in 2022, and since 2023, I've had about 4. I can't get any certifications because they are all $600, and fighting ADHD kills some days for me, but I look for jobs every day. I've applied to over 1000 jobs - most entry level, but I can't seem to gain traction. I am not necessarily even looking for jobs solely in my degree's specialties! I have applied for part time jobs at retail and been turned down.

I'm so tired of rejection, being ghosted, and being told hundreds of different ways to present myself/resume/and how to find a job. I just want a job that allows me to actually pay rent, have a car, and feed myself. Any offers I've had have been under 40k/year, which is NOT a survivable wage in my area. 

:: My bachelor's degree is information systems management and business analytics with a minor in IT management, and my master's is in IT management and cyber security.:: 

AND BEFORE YOU SAY IT, I know that cyber security is impossible to get in right now, and it's not my major focus. My desire is to be an IT Auditor (Perfect for my ADHD), but I am willing to work my way from the bottom up.

*ETA: I'm female and battling that hurdle as well.*

ETAAAAAA: YOU GUYS. thank you so much for your advice and help and offers. I am definitely making some changes to how I do things, and all of your advice has been very helpful. I think that there is definitely something wrong with my resume, I just don't know what it is and I need to fix it. I am very motivated despite all the rejection but it is definitely a difficult thing. I can't thank you enough for all the advice. Please keep it coming and I will address all the people who requested my resume as soon as I can. This is just been so helpful and made me so hopeful. I really appreciate everybody. Xoxox

data.title: Im a veteran about to be homeless looking for some help so I don't have to live in my car

images.description:
Im a an Air Force veteran trying to get disability from the VA for crippling depression, anxiety, and PTSD. I've been struggling to stay employed. I am 2 months past due on my rent and im going to be homeless in a couple of days. My cat is the only good thing that I have in my life. I found someone that boards cats in NC and is willing to take care of him. He will be around other cats and won't be in a cage and I will get to visit him to let him know I am not giving him up. My current plan is to live in my car until I can get a job and save up enough money to find a place to live. I couldn't raise enough to avoid the eviction but I made my past due car insurance and a car payment so at least I wont lose my car. I don't have any friends or family that can help me and no place to go but I am determined to make it work. Im trying to hold on and hoping that that things can and might get better but I am so tired and scared. I have a kofi and gofundme for anyone that would like to help. Anything at all will make a huge difference in helping me find a place to live with my cat. Even just an upvote or comment can be a big help. If there is anybody  near Raleigh, NC that could help me please DM me. Thank you so much.

data.title: I just finished painting this portrait of Lady Diana!

images.description:
After working on it for more than 2 months, I finally just finished working on this massive oil painting of a woman that the whole world loves and misses, Lady Diana. I chose to portray her with her sons instead of as a princess wearing royal jewelry because I think the world remembers her first and foremost as a loving mother.

If this is the first time you come across me, I'm a 20-year-old, self-taught artist. Thank you all so much for all of your support! I wouldn't be the young artist that I am without all of your support. Thank you all very much! I love you all!

If you'd like to see all of my artworks, you can on my website anisjerbi.com and if you'd like to commission an artwork from me or purchase one of my artworks, please contact me. This oil painting is also for sale, so if you're interested in purchasing it, make sure you contact me.

26 years ago today, Lady Diana passed away.
May she rest in peace.

It's going extremely viral on Instagram which is so awesome! It'd be amazing if a member of the Royal family will reach out to me. Maybe Harry or William. I doubt Charles... for... you know... obvious... reasons...

data.title: A great technique to getting nice legs
Oatmeal Cream Pies that would make Little Debbie exile herself!

images.description: Stack O Pies! This made about 14 pies. Not my recipe, but I tweaked it for flavor and altitude (I'm at 4500ft). I used about 1 3/4 tsp of pumpkin spice in place of 1 tsp cinnamon and halved the baking soda. For the filling, I used vanilla bean paste, added nutmeg to taste, and used heavy cream instead of milk. I baked for 14 minutes instead of 12. I used a Kitchenaid mixer, Le Creuset baking sheets (they bake very evenly), and I weighed my ingredients with a digital kitchen scale. I also added in the powdered sugar slowly by heaping spoonfuls instead of messing with a food processor - no sugar explosion!
Mmmm...fluff...

I just thought this is worth sharing. Some of the lesser known subtle signs a normally very friendly dog can show before a snap happens. This is not blaming anyone! Just some info, that's all

images.description: Obviously dogs yawn when tired, however if you are talking to a dog you meet, or your child is, and you see them yawn it's a warning sign. Same thing if a dog is licking it's lips and there's no food around.

Not everyone loves dogs, or has been around many of them. Even people who have been, don't know all the signs, so this post is purely to show that there are signs a dog is about to snap before they get to the growling stage. It's not to patronise, or anything else like that. Just a fyi post, or a reminder.  

We hear a lot in the news "it was a sudden attack" "there was no warning". However the large majority of the time the signs were actually there. However dogs can go from ears back straight to a bite. Not all dogs have the patience to go through every single step of warning.

The rare case a dog goes from happily playing to biting is because they were touched somewhere they were sore. That's what happened to me when a Old English sheep dog bit my face when I was 3yrs old. I touched his ear and it turned out he had an ear infection, I needed multiple stitches obviously. So I'm not saying that never happens, just it's a very small percentage compared to missing/not knowing the signs. 

When I'm out with my 5yr old and a dog owner says "oh he can pat him/her" I make sure to keep an eye at all times for the signs above. I never believe the "my dog never bites". There's a first time for everything, so knowing the signs can reduce the risk greatly. 

I grew up with dogs my entire life, around all types of animals, anyone who says they know everything is talking shite. So please if I've missed anything, inform me! It's the only way any of us learn! These warning signs are real though so please don't dismiss them

I thought I'd be public enemy number one as a foreigner but my friend saw my potential and backed me when everyone else said he was crazy. Unfortunately, it seems like my success bred some resentment and his contract wasn't renewed for another term. data.title: A medium sized dump and a request for help.

images.description: Well, hey folks. Its been awhile since I posted any memes - its been a rough few months. Recently, I was diagnosed with cervical cancer. I had another procedure today and am now stuck waiting up to two weeks to be told whether it has spread or not. Ive never actually come to the Imgur community for help like this before, but Im pretty concerned about my financial stability through all this and in America, the financial crisis that comes from overcoming cancer is often worse than the actual illness. In light of that, I made a PayPal fundraiser. I have no idea what Im doing or what happens next, but if you felt like donating I would of course be incredibly grateful.

https://www.paypal.com/pools/c/8Xdrp5xVYv 

Thats the link. And if anything, please take this advice away from this post: dont put it off. Dont put it off. I mean it. And if you do see a doctor and they try to dismiss your concerns, please please please advocate for yourself and push them to keep looking for whatever is wrong. Im in the situation Im in right now because I was told that whatever I was feeling wasnt that serious - this should have been caught years ago, and now Im going through possibly the worse medical scare of my life so far. Please just stand up for yourself if you really feel like youre not being heard.
